You may pay by electronic check or credit card by going to "My Public Records Request Center" and select "View My Invoices." Then scroll to find your open invoice and select "Make Payment." Follow the screen prompts to make a payment. 
 
Mailing a check could delay the response time and it is preferable that you use the online payment portal to make an electronic payment. However, if you need to mail a check, please reply to this message and ask for the correct address. Please be sure and provide your Reference Number (C384715-022525) on your check. 
 
Please be advised that pursuant to ORS 192.329(3)(b) and (4)(b), your public records request will be closed if payment is not received within sixty (60) days of this invoice. 
 
 
Sincerely, 
 
 
City of Portland Public Records Responder 
 
 
 *Please note that you will need to disable your pop-up blocker on your browser's settings in order to make an online payment.
*Please see this Answer for more information:  A006257-010816 If you are having technical difficulties with the website, please contact the website administrator by phone or email.  (503) 823-6040 or prrhelp@portlandoregon.gov

Dear Jordan, 

No payment was made on the initial invoice so instead of requiring you to make any additional request for the report or video that we can provide, on 3/12 we modified the invoice to show a charge for the full report and video to process on this single request.  A bit later you messaged that a check was being sent.

title: Public Records Request for Bodycam, Dashcam, and Related Footage – Arrests of Four Suspects on January 10, 2025

communications.subject: Rhode Island Access to Public Records Act Request: Public Records Request for Bodycam, Dashcam, and Related Footage – Arrests of Four Suspects on January 10, 2025
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Rhode Island Access to Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I respectfully request access to the following records related to the arrests of four individuals on January 10, 2025, following a vehicle pursuit that ended near the Providence/Cranston line on Interstate 95:

Body-worn camera footage from all Providence Police Department officers involved in the pursuit, apprehension, and arrest of the suspects.

Dashcam footage from all patrol units engaged in the pursuit and subsequent arrest operations.

Rear-seat vehicle footage from the patrol units that transported the suspects following their arrests.

Incident reports or arrest reports relating the incident.

This request focuses on essential records that document the pursuit, apprehension, and arrest of the suspects involved in the armed robbery of a FedEx driver in Harvard, Massachusetts, and the subsequent pursuit that concluded in Providence, Rhode Island. If any additional footage (such as surveillance or helicopter footage) exists and provides significant context to the events, I request access to those records as well.

If it helps to locate the desired incident, here's a news report: https://www.wpri.com/news/local-news/providence/bodycam-video-shows-arrest-of-4-suspects-in-fedex-driver-robbery/

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Police Cam News

communications.subject: FOIL Request :: W138532-110224
communications.communication:
Dear Brad: 
 
Thank you for your Freedom of Information Law (FOIL) request. Your request has been received and is being processed. Your request was received in this office on 11/2/2024 and given the reference number FOIL #W138532-110224 for tracking purposes. You may expect the Department's response to your request no later than 12/5/2024. 
 
Record Requested: To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records:

Copies of any and all correspondence to or from any and all DEC staff and officials and to or from personnel in their offices (including without limitation all email correspondence sent to or from any email address within the @dec.ny.gov domain) referencing or pertaining to the seizure and subsequent killing of animals seized from the Chemung County home of Mark Longo (i.e. Peanut the Squirrel) in October/November 2024.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brad Aaron

Upload documents directly: https://accounts.muckrock.com/accounts/login/?next=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.muckrock.com%2Faccounts%2Flogin%2F%3Fnext%3D%252Faccounts%252Fagency_login%252Fnew-york-state-department-environmental-conservation-4382%252Fnys-dec-records-pertaining-to-seizure-and-extermination-of-pets-from-private-homes-175647%252F%253Femail%253Daccess.records%252540dec.ny.gov&url_auth_token=AAAT6EkeGziaMT7FfqZM4erB6Dc%3A1t78V0%3AaqHpM47KvCggv7vOM9RptzSrXO73AuFmncqWI_WyPhU

Dear Brad Aaron 

This is in response to your 11/2/2024 3:25:54 AM Freedom of Information Law (FOIL) request seeking: To Whom It May Concern: 

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records: 

Copies of any and all correspondence to or from any and all DEC staff and officials and to or from personnel in their offices (including without limitation all email correspondence sent to or from any email address within the @dec.ny.gov domain) referencing or pertaining to the seizure and subsequent killing of animals seized from the Chemung County home of Mark Longo (i.e. Peanut the Squirrel) in October/November 2024. 

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. 

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not. 

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response The Department of Environmental Conservation (DEC) has identified records responsive to your request and has uploaded those records into DEC's online FOIL request system.  Please visit the customer portal for DEC's online system by clicking here to log into your DEC FOIL account, where you can view and download the records. Be advised that DEC has withheld certain responsive documents or portions thereof from disclosure in accordance with one or more of the following provisions of Public Officers Law (POL) § 87 2.: 
 
  *  POL 87.2.a. Records are specifically exempted from disclosure by state or federal statute. 
  *  POL 87.2.b. Would constitute an unwarranted invasion of personal privacy under POL 89.2. 
  *  POL 87.2.e. Records are compiled for law enforcement purposes. 
  *  POL 87.2.f. Records if disclosed could endanger the life or safety of any person. POL 87.2.g. Inter-agency or intra-agency materials. If you believe you have been unlawfully denied access to records, you have the right to appeal.  Any such appeal must be submitted in writing and within thirty (30) days of the date of this email.  Appeals must be directed to: FOIL Appeals Officer 
Office of General Counsel 
New York State Department of Environmental Conservation 
625 Broadway, 14th Floor 
Albany, NY 12233-1500 Your FOIL request is now closed.  Please reference FOIL W138532-110224 in all future correspondence with DEC concerning this request.  Thank you. Sincerely, Records Access

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Brady List (March 2025) (Okanogan County Prosecuting Attorney)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

All current "Brady lists" and "Giglio lists" (per Brady v. Maryland/Giglio v. United States) maintained by your office.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Rose Terse

communications.subject: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: Untitled
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records:

All communications in your possession, of any type whatsoever, to and from the Five-Borough Chamber Alliance and/or its members, including but not limited to Lisa Sorin, President of the Bronx Chamber of Commerce;  Randy Peers, President and CEO of the Brooklyn Chamber of Commerce; Jessica Walker, President and CEO of the Manhattan Chamber of Commerce; Tom Grech, President and CEO of the Queens Chamber of Commerce; and Linda Baran, President and CEO of the Staten Island Chamber of Commerce

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jake Offenhartz

communications.subject: RE: New York Freedom of Information Law Request #FOIL-2022-002-00407
communications.communication:
Dear FOIL Appeals Officer,

I am writing in regard to Freedom of Information Law request sent to the City on 05/03/2022 (attached.)

Please consider this a formal appeal under Public Officers Law 89(4)(A) of the constructive denial of that request. I say constructive denial because the City has simply failed to respond in a timely manner to my request.

In a FOIL request I submitted on 05/03/2022 I asked for “All communications in your possession, of any type whatsoever, to and from the Five-Borough Chamber Alliance and/or its members, including but not limited to Lisa Sorin, President of the Bronx Chamber of Commerce; Randy Peers, President and CEO of the Brooklyn Chamber of Commerce; Jessica Walker, President and CEO of the Manhattan Chamber of Commerce; Tom Grech, President and CEO of the Queens Chamber of Commerce; and Linda Baran, President and CEO of the Staten Island Chamber of Commerce."

It has been more than two years. To date, I have received neither the records sought nor a denial of the request. I received recognition of my FOIL request but have not received further communication, the requested documents, or a denial.

The city's approach to my request is simply unlawful. It is inconsistent with both the language and intent of FOIL.

As the state’s Committee on Open Government, tasked with interpreting FOIL matters, has said, under FOIL, “an agency cannot engage in one delay after another.” FOIL AO-18008(Feb. 22, 2010). Yet, this is exactly how the city council has responded to my request, sending me only one correspondence.

Pursuant to Public Officers Law 89(3)(a), as amended by the Legislature in 2005, an agency must within five business days of receipt of a written request for records make the record sought available, deny access and give reasons for the denial, or furnish an acknowledgement of receipt and state the approximate date when the request will be dealt with. The statute further specifies that the approximate date for addressing a request on its merits should not exceed 20 business days from the date of the acknowledgement of the receipt of the request. A failure by an agency to conform to this statutorily mandated time frame constitutes a constructive denial. See Public Officers Law 89(4)(a). The statute was written as such to ensure FOIL requestors are not, as here, subjected to endless delays by agencies that choose to open their files to the public (which was precisely why FOIL was passed in the first place).

Indeed, the Committee on Open Government makes clear that “in the rare situation in which it is found that more than 20 additional business days are needed [to address the merits of a request], the agency may do so, with an explanation of the reason for the delay and an indication of a “date certain,” a self-imposed deadline by which it will grant access to the records in whole or in part (see regulations of the Committee on Open Government, 21 NYCRR 1401.5). When the date certain is reasonable in consideration of attendant facts and circumstances, the agency would be complying with law. There is no provision that permits agencies to indicate extension after extension.” FOIL AO-18008 (emphasis added). See also FOIL-AO 16095 (Dec. 13, 2007) (noting that “the amendments [to FOIL] clearly are intended to prohibit agencies from unnecessarily delaying disclosure.”). A series of generic notifications over a period of months saying that a response is forthcoming does not meet this standard under FOIL.

Further, as recognized by the New York Court of Appeals, FOIL itself contains “the Legislature’s own unmistakably broad declaration that … it is incumbent upon the state and its localities to extend public accountability wherever and whenever feasible.” Westchester Newspapers, Inc. v Kimball, 50 NY2d 575,579 (1980) (emphasis added), quoting Section 84 of FOIL. Therefore, where, as here, records are clearly available to the public under FOIL, or are readily retrievable, there may be no basis for a delay in disclosures.

As I know of no grounds in FOIL for the denial of the request, and the city has given none, I ask that this appeal be granted and that the records sought be produced promptly.

Thank you

Jake Offenhartz
Associated Press
212 621 1605

title: Tennessee Open Records Act Request – September 20, 2022 Arrest of Tarius Sledge at East Ridge High School

communications.subject: Tennessee Public Records Act Request: Tennessee Open Records Act Request – September 20, 2022 Arrest of Tarius Sledge at East Ridge High School
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Tennessee Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I respectfully request access to and copies of all records pertaining to the arrest of Tarius Sledge on September 20, 2022, at East Ridge High School in East Ridge, Tennessee. Mr. Sledge, an 18-year-old student, was involved in an altercation with School Resource Deputy (SRD) Tyler McRae during a gym class session. The incident escalated when Mr. Sledge allegedly refused to comply with instructions, leading to a physical confrontation that included SRD McRae pulling Mr. Sledge by his hair and deploying pepper spray. This event was partially captured on video, which subsequently circulated widely on social media platforms.

I am seeking the following records related to this incident:

All available body-worn camera footage from SRD Tyler McRae and any other officers present during the incident, including the entirety of the interaction with Mr. Sledge.
All available surveillance footage from East Ridge High School's gymnasium and surrounding areas capturing the incident.
The complete incident and arrest reports, including all officer narratives, supplemental reports, and witness statements from school staff, students, and other individuals present.
All 911 call recordings and dispatch logs related to this incident, including radio communications and Computer-Aided Dispatch (CAD) reports.
Any photographs taken by the Hamilton County Sheriff's Office during or after the incident, including images of Mr. Sledge, the involved officers, and the location of the altercation.
The full arrest affidavits and any related charging documents filed in this case.
Any internal reviews, use-of-force reports, or investigations conducted by the Hamilton County Sheriff's Office regarding this incident.
Any press releases, social media posts, or official statements made by the Hamilton County Sheriff's Office or East Ridge High School regarding this incident.
The primary goal of this request is to serve the public interest by making these records publicly accessible. While I acknowledge that I may also generate revenue from disseminating these materials, the request primarily aims to enhance transparency regarding this law enforcement incident.

I request a waiver of fees associated with fulfilling this request, as disclosure of the requested information will contribute to public understanding of law enforcement practices and actions within educational settings. However, if a full fee waiver is not possible, please inform me of the estimated costs in advance. Additionally, if fees can be reduced or eliminated by excluding certain records, please specify which records those would be.

Please provide the records in an electronic format if available. If any portions of this request are denied, please cite the specific legal exemption(s) and provide a redacted version of the document where applicable.

I appreciate your time and assistance in this matter.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 7 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Kent Hoover, a citizen of Tennessee, in coordination with Police Cam News.

title: Public Records Request – Records Pertaining to the Arrest of Nicholas Jones on May 5, 2019

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Public Records Request – Records Pertaining to the Arrest of Nicholas Jones on May 5, 2019
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

I hereby request copies of all records related to the arrest of Nicholas Jones on May 5, 2019, in St. Johns County, Florida. This incident involved Mr. Jones allegedly fleeing a traffic stop and subsequently calling 911 to report and boast about the incident, leading to his arrest.

1. **Incident and Arrest Reports:**
   - The complete incident report, arrest report, and any supplementary narratives authored by the responding deputies concerning this event.
   - Any written statements provided by Mr. Jones during the incident or subsequent arrest process.

2. **Audio and Video Recordings:**
   - All available dashcam and body-worn camera footage capturing the initial traffic stop, pursuit, arrest, and any interactions with Mr. Jones.
   - Audio recordings of 911 calls, including the call made by Mr. Jones, radio communications, and dispatch logs related to this incident.

3. **Evidence Documentation:**
   - Records detailing any evidence collected during the investigation, including descriptions of items found in Mr. Jones's vehicle at the time of arrest.
   - Inventory logs of any items seized from the vehicle or from Mr. Jones at the time of arrest.

4. **Internal Communications and Reports:**
   - Internal memos, emails, or communications within the St. Johns County Sheriff's Office pertaining to this incident.
   - Any reports or assessments generated as a result of this incident, including procedural reviews or evaluations.

I request that these records be provided in electronic format, if available, to facilitate prompt and efficient processing.

**Fee Disclosure and Request for Estimate:**
I acknowledge that this request is being made for commercial purposes. Therefore, I am prepared to incur any applicable fees associated with the processing of this request. To manage costs effectively, I kindly ask that you provide an itemized estimate of the anticipated fees prior to fulfilling the request. If certain documents can be excluded to reduce costs, please inform me so that I can make an informed decision on how to proceed.

If any portion of this request is denied or if specific documents are withheld, please cite the specific statutory exemption that justifies the refusal. Additionally, if certain records are only partially exempt, I request that the non-exempt portions be disclosed after appropriate redaction, as stipulated by the Florida Public Records Act.

Please confirm receipt of this request and provide an estimated timeline for its fulfillment.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Police Cam News

communications.subject: RE: Florida Sunshine Law Request #R030203-031625
communications.communication:
Apologies for the confusion, unfortunately info like the specific time or case number doesn't seem to be publicly available, but I can help with mapping out a timeline for the case events.

Initial Event: Nicholas Jones allegedly fled from a traffic stop conducted by deputies in St. Johns County.

Shortly After: He then called 911 to taunt law enforcement, reportedly saying:

“I like ran from a cop 30 minutes to an hour ago. I was the guy... that over there off of Kings Estates Road. Like what do we pay you guys for?”

Follow-Up: After tracing the phone number and investigating, deputies located and arrested him shortly after the 911 call.

He reportedly admitted during questioning that he “thought it would be funny” and didn’t expect to get caught.

According to reports from First Coast News and The Florida Times-Union, the charges included:​

Reckless Driving

Fleeing and Eluding Law Enforcement

Misuse of 911

Violation of Probation

Here's a news article regarding the case: https://www.firstcoastnews.com/article/news/florida-man-calls-911-to-brag-after-fleeing-traffic-stop-like-what-do-we-pay-you-guys-for/77-e6844799-d7ec-4807-ab9b-c390f3cacb05

Apologies for the lack of specifics, if there are any problems, don't hesitate to contact me and I will be happy to withdraw the request if it's not possible or too burdensome to locate the desired incident.

communications.communication:

RE: PUBLIC RECORDS REQUEST of March 16, 2025, Reference # R030203-031625. 
Dear Police News, 
The St. Johns County Sheriff's Office received a public information request from you on March 16, 2025. Your request mentioned: “To Whom It May Concern: 

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records: 

I hereby request copies of all records related to the arrest of Nicholas Jones on May 5, 2019, in St. Johns County, Florida. This incident involved Mr. Jones allegedly fleeing a traffic stop and subsequently calling 911 to report and boast about the incident, leading to his arrest. 

1. **Incident and Arrest Reports:** 
- The complete incident report, arrest report, and any supplementary narratives authored by the responding deputies concerning this event. 
- Any written statements provided by Mr. Jones during the incident or subsequent arrest process. 

2. **Audio and Video Recordings:** 
- All available dashcam and body-worn camera footage capturing the initial traffic stop, pursuit, arrest, and any interactions with Mr. Jones. 
- Audio recordings of 911 calls, including the call made by Mr. Jones, radio communications, and dispatch logs related to this incident. 

3. **Evidence Documentation:** 
- Records detailing any evidence collected during the investigation, including descriptions of items found in Mr. Jones's vehicle at the time of arrest. 
- Inventory logs of any items seized from the vehicle or from Mr. Jones at the time of arrest. 

4. **Internal Communications and Reports:** 
- Internal memos, emails, or communications within the St. Johns County Sheriff's Office pertaining to this incident. 
- Any reports or assessments generated as a result of this incident, including procedural reviews or evaluations. 

I request that these records be provided in electronic format, if available, to facilitate prompt and efficient processing. 

**Fee Disclosure and Request for Estimate:** 
I acknowledge that this request is being made for commercial purposes. Therefore, I am prepared to incur any applicable fees associated with the processing of this request. To manage costs effectively, I kindly ask that you provide an itemized estimate of the anticipated fees prior to fulfilling the request. If certain documents can be excluded to reduce costs, please inform me so that I can make an informed decision on how to proceed. 

If any portion of this request is denied or if specific documents are withheld, please cite the specific statutory exemption that justifies the refusal. Additionally, if certain records are only partially exempt, I request that the non-exempt portions be disclosed after appropriate redaction, as stipulated by the Florida Public Records Act. 

Please confirm receipt of this request and provide an estimated timeline for its fulfillment. 

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. 

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not. 

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days. 

Sincerely, 

Police Cam News

title: GA CVR Collection (2020, 2022) (Jones County Elections Office)

communications.subject: Georgia Open Records Act Request: GA CVR Collection (2020, 2022) (Jones County Elections Office)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Georgia Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Cast vote record (CVR) data for the following elections:
1. 2020 Nov General Election
2. 2022 Nov Midterm Election

Specifically, I’m looking for the full anonymized record of votes cast each election generated by the Dominion voting system. Forsyth County has an example of these records posted for the 2024 General Election under the name “Cast Vote Records (CVR) Report” at this link: https://www.forsythco.com/Departments-Offices/Voter-Registrations-Elections/Election-Results. Please let me know if you need any further clarification on the type of data that I am requesting.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Aleksandra Conevska

title: Special Education Quality Assurance Nondistrict Program Review, Élan School

communications.subject: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: Special Education Quality Assurance Nondistrict Program Review, Élan School
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records:

A complete copy of the "Final Report" (dated November 2, 2005) of the "Special Education Quality Assurance" "Nondistrict Program Review" for Élan School (located in the town of Poland, Maine, USA; zipcode 04274), created by NYSED Special Education Quality Assurance (likely its "Nondistrict Unit" specifically).

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Nanci Brown

communications.subject: RE: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: Special Education Quality Assurance Nondistrict Program Review, Élan School
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Brown:

This is to acknowledge receipt of your Freedom of Information Law (FOIL) request for State Education Department (SED) records regarding SEQA Nondistrict Program Review.  The reference number for this request is FL-EM-25/309.   Please be advised that you will hear further from the Department by approximately April 16, 2025 as to whether your request will be granted or denied in whole or in part.

SED charges the statutorily permitted fees under FOIL. These include $.25 per page for photocopies or the actual cost of reproducing records requested under FOIL (Public Officers Law §87[1][b][iii]). Payment must be made to the NYS Education Department by check or money order. Do not send any payment until you are notified that your request is granted and informed of the charge for your request. If your request is granted, the records will be provided to you in the manner requested (i.e. hardcopy or electronic), or if not specified, in a reasonable manner selected by this office.

If your request is granted, and there is a fee, one of the following will happen:

1. If your request can be filled immediately, and the total photocopy or reproduction fee is under $25.00, staff will forward the requested records to you with a statement what you owe. Or:

2. If the reproduction fee or photocopy fee for your request is $25.00 or more, you will be advised of the page count (+100 pages) or other expenses and the fee(s) owed in advance of our providing the records. Upon receipt of payment, staff will photocopy or otherwise reproduce the requested records and transmit, as appropriate. Or:

3. If it will take time to locate and/or photocopy or otherwise reproduce the records you have requested, you will be given a date by which you will be provided with a page count and/or estimated cost to fulfil your request.

Please note, there is no provision in law or regulation requiring the waiver of a fee under FOIL.
Regards,
Records Access Officer

communications.subject: FL-EM-25-309 Brown FOIL Response

communications.subject: New Jersey Open Public Records Act Request: Flock camera records request
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New Jersey Open Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Dear Public Records Officer,

I am requesting copies of all invoices from Flock Safety for the period of 1/1/2024 to the present. Please ensure that all pages of each invoice are included, including any itemized lists detailing equipment, software, or services provided.

If available, I prefer to receive the records in electronic format via email. If any fees apply, please inform me before processing the request. Should any portion of this request be denied, please provide the specific legal basis for the denial.

Thank you for your time and assistance. I look forward to your response within the statutory timeframe.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 7 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Nicholas Schroeder

communications.subject: RE: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: FOIA Request: FY25 Organized Retail Crime Grant Program
communications.communication:
Dear MuckRock News:

The Village does not have any application in its possession or control.  Village personnel applied for the Organized Retail Crime Grant through an online portal administered by the Illinois Attorney General’s Office.  We are not sure how other law enforcement agencies completed an application.  They may have prepared a paper application or have print-outs from the Attorney General’s online portal.  But the Village of La Grange does not.  We cannot provide you records we do not have.

To the extent that you desire to see the application materials completed in the online portal, you may want to submit a request to the Illinois Attorney General’s Office.  We assume that the Attorney General’s Office has copies of all information submitted.

Thank you


[cid:image002.png@01DB9500.D12604F0]

communications.subject: RE: Maryland Public Information Act Request #DIS#56193
communications.communication:
Hi Keith,

Of course -- let me know if this explanation is more clear. 

Essentially I'm trying to figure out what specific offenses each of these offense category labels are associated with (where they occur in state law). For example, it's not immediately clear to me what level or type of offense "DRUGS - ASSOCIATED" or "PUBLIC ORDER - TRAFFIC" are linked to. I was told by someone far more familiar with Maryland government than me to ask for JIS numbers for each of these offense categories, but it's possible they confused a terminology or that it's not universal throughout the courts / DPSCS. 

Does that make more sense? If not, please let me know if you have time for a quick phone call. 

Gratefully,
Jacob

communications.subject: Re: Maryland Public Information Act Request #DIS#56193
communications.communication:
Yes sir, makes perfect sense. I will work on getting you that info now!

Keith

title: School Based Arrest Public Record Request (Methuen Public Schools)

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: School Based Arrest Public Record Request (Methuen Public Schools)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

This letter constitutes a request pursuant to the Public Records Act, G.L. c.66, §10, for public records in the custody of your school district. Under the Criminal Justice Reform Act,  school districts and law enforcement agencies must “specify the manner and division of responsibility for collecting and reporting the school-based arrests, citations and court referrals of students to the Department of Elementary and Secondary Education” (DESE).   DESE began collecting data on school-related arrests in the 2018-19 school year. In the 2019-20 school year, DESE has expanded that collection to include data on all referrals to law enforcement.  DESE has defined these terms as follows, borrowing the same definitions used by the U.S. Department of Education since its 2009 Civil Rights Data Collection.  

A school-related arrest “[r]efers to an arrest of a student for any activity conducted on school grounds, during off campus school activities (including while taking school transportation), or due to a referral by any school official. All school-related arrests are considered referrals to law enforcement.”  

A referral to law enforcement “[i]s an action by which a student is reported to any law enforcement agency or official, including a school police unit, for an incident that occurs on school grounds, during school-related events, or while taking school transportation, regardless of whether official action is taken. Citations, tickets, court referrals, and school-related arrests are considered referrals to law enforcement.”   

I request the following public records, as defined in G. L. c. 4, § 7 (twenty-sixth): 
1.	An extract of your records management system or database that includes each school-related arrest and each referral to law enforcement conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022 school year (up until the day the records are produced). Specifically, we request an extract of the database to include the following columns:
a.	Date of arrest or referral to law enforcement
b.	Time of arrest or referral to law enforcement
c.	Charge (or charges)
d.	Whether the individual(s) was arrested or referred to law enforcement
e.	Sex of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
f.	Age of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
g.	Race of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
h.	Ethnicity of individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
i.	Disability status of the individual(s) arrested or referred to law enforcement
j.	Whether the individual arrested or referred to law enforcement is a student at the school.
k.	Name of arresting officer, if applicable, and 
l.	Badge number of the arresting officer or the officer that referred the youth to law enforcement, as applicable.

2.	If such an extract of the database in question 1 is not possible, please provide school incident reports on each school-related arrest and referral to law enforcement conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022 school year (up until the day the records are produced). 

3.	A copy of any active standard operating procedures developed with the police department and/or other law enforcement agencies regarding police placement or activity in your corresponding school;  and,

4.	Any records instructing or informing police personnel of, or otherwise describing data reporting requirements and procedures for complying with G.L. c. 71 § 37P(b).

5.	The cost to the school district of assigning a school resource officer to each school; and, 

6.	The total number of school resource officers and total number of guidance counselors for each school in your district for school years 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and,

7.	The total number and a brief description of 911 calls from schools in your district to local police departments conducted during the 2018-2019, 2019-2020, 2020-2021, and 2021-2022, and, 

8.	A description of the proposed budget for mental, social, or emotional health support personnel for the school district.

As this request involves a matter of public interest and will not be used for any commercial purpose, we ask that all fees associated with this request be waived pursuant to 950 C.M.R. 32.07(2)(k). The purpose of this request is to determine whether your school district and police department are complying with their reporting obligations under the Criminal Justice Reform Act.  “The public has an interest in knowing whether public servants are carrying out their duties in an efficient and law-abiding manner.”    

It would be ill-advised to impose a fee for data that your school district may have failed to report in violation of statutory and regulatory duty.  Moreover, as you know, municipalities with a population of over 20,000 may not assess a fee for the first 2 hours of time spent searching for, compiling, segregating, redacting and reproducing a requested record. Finally, pursuant to 950 C.M.R. 32.07(2)(i), a records access officer shall assess no fee greater than the lowest hourly rate of a person capable of compiling, segregating, redacting and reproducing a requested record. In the event that a charge is incurred for this request which you will not waive, please so indicate and include an itemization of estimated good faith costs.
 
Please provide public records to a requestor in an electronic format unless the record is not available in an electronic format. G.L.c. 66, § 6A(d). 

The Public Records Act requires that you comply with this request within ten (10) business days following receipt. If you believe that documents or data responsive to any request herein is not public record and thus not subject to disclosure, please set forth in writing the specific reasons for such assertion, including the specific exemption or exemptions that you believe apply.  To the extent that you determine that records need to be redacted in order to be produced under any law protecting the privacy of named individuals, please do so rather than withholding them in their entirety.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days. If you have any questions about this request, or need additional time to respond, please contact me by phone at (617)-338-1050 or by email at Erinstewart@cfjj.org. Thank you in advance for your prompt response to this request.

Sincerely,

Erin Stewart
Citizens for Juvenile Justice

communications.subject: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: Soccer
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records:

- Copy of the signed Letter of Intent with Jeff Buell (or related entity) regarding the proposed Liberty Park soccer project as reported in the Times Union.

- Copy of any related agreements signed with Jeff Buell (or related entity) regarding proposed soccer project. 

- Documentation of any payments made by Jeff Buell (or related entity) to Capitalize Albany in 2024.

- Copy of any planning studies prepared by Capitalize Albany or its consultants between 2020-2025 regarding the overall redevelopment of Liberty Park.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

WarrenG

communications.subject: City of Seattle Public Records Request Center - Invoice Ready :: C201984-102124
communications.communication:
Dear Rose Terse, 
 
Records in response to your public disclosure request C201984-102124 received on October 21, 2024 are now available. The cost for the records is as follows: 
 
Invoice Number: INV24-C201984-1 
Total: $1.25 
 
To pay online, please follow these steps: 
 Please note that you will need to disable any pop-up blockers to make a payment using the system. 
 
  * Navigate to the Public Records Request Center.
  * Select 'My Records Request Center'. 
  * Select 'View My Requests'. You may be asked to login. 
  * Find this request: C201984-102124. 
  * Select the 'View Invoices' button. 
 
  * Opens a pop-up window showing your invoice: INV24-C201984-1. 
  * Click on the invoice and then the 'Pay Now' button. 
  * Continue processing your payment. 
  * Select 'Done'. 
  * Once the payment process is done, you are returned to the Public Records Request Center. 
  * After your payment is successful you will receive an email from our payments center. 
Once your payment has been approved, we will send you an email with instructions on how to download your records. Note that City staff must manually upload records. Records will be available one to two business days after payment. 
 
Please let your public disclosure officer (PDO) know if you are unable to pay online; your PDO will work with you on alternative ways to make your payment. 
 
You have 30 days from today's date to pay for your records. If the City does not receive your payment within this time period, your request will be considered abandoned, and you will need to submit a new request. 
 Please add seattle@mycusthelp.net to your E-mail contacts/address book to ensure delivery of the record center E-mails to your Inbox. (mailto:seattle@mycusthelp.net) 
This is an auto-generated email and has originated from an unmonitored email account. Please DO NOT REPLY.

title: Request for Body Cam Footage of Arrest – Bonnie Campbell

communications.subject: Oklahoma Open Records Act Request: Request for Body Cam Footage of Arrest – Bonnie Campbell
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Oklahoma Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Incident Details for Footage Retrieval:

Date: September 29, 2024
Location: Tulsa, OK (Airport)
Suspect: Bonnie Campbell, 53
Incident Summary:
Bonnie Campbell was arrested for allegedly driving under the influence (DUI) on an airport runway. Air traffic control reported that she was blocking the runway and driving around it. Officers arrived and took her into custody, during which she admitted to drinking prior to and while parked at the airport. Officers also noted that this was the second consecutive day they had received reports of her driving under the influence at the airport.
I am requesting copies of all body-worn camera footage from officers who:

Responded to the DUI call at the airport.
Interacted with and questioned Campbell.
Placed Campbell under arrest and transported her.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Harun
